data.text:
List of Manchester bands, listed by their level of fame. This Manchester musicians list includes both bands and solo artists. All famous Manchester bands are included, as well as many Manchester musicians of underground status. This list of Manchester musical artists includes information like what genre the artist falls under, what albums they've put out and more. If you want to know more about these famous Manchester bands you can click on their names to learn more about them. Bands from every genre are listed here, including rock, pop, hip-hop/rap, jazz, and more.

List features bands like Oasis and The Smiths.

If you're wondering, "What bands are from Manchester?" or "What is a list of Manchester bands?" then this list will answer your questions. {#nodes}

Ranked by

Rock music, Britpop, Alternative rock

Albums : (What's the Story) Morning Glory?, Definitely Maybe, Don’t Believe the Truth, Dig Out Your Soul, Be Here Now

Oasis undoubtedly sits at the pinnacle of Manchester's music scene, with their working-class roots and aggressive, in-your-face rock'n'roll sound epitomizing the city's spirit and attitude. Formed in 1991 by brothers Liam and Noel Gallagher, the band's meteoric rise to fame was driven by an unyielding determination and a relentless gigging schedule, helping to spark a cultural revolution in the mid-90s referred to as 'Britpop.' Their albums Definitely Maybe and (What's the Story) Morning Glory? remain iconic masterpieces, filled with memorable anthems that capture the essence of Manchester and showcase the city's indelible mark on the global music stage.

Indie rock, Jangle pop, Post-punk

Albums : The Queen Is Dead, Meat Is Murder, The Smiths, Hatful of Hollow, Louder Than Bombs

Formed in 1982, The Smiths' influential sound and evocative lyrics have solidified their status as one of Manchester's most cherished bands. With their distinct blend of jangle-pop and post-punk elements, the group's innovative style was inspired by the city's gritty, industrial backdrop, encapsulating the social zeitgeist and providing an emotive soundtrack for a generation. Frontman Morrissey's haunting vocals and introspective songwriting, combined with Johnny Marr's intricate guitar work, cemented The Smiths' place in music history, pushing the boundaries of Manchester's music scene and setting the stage for countless indie-rock bands that would follow in their wake.

Electronica, Big Beat, Techno

Albums : Dig Your Own Hole, Surrender, Exit Planet Dust, Come With Us, Further

The Chemical Brothers' genre-defying approach to electronic music has made them a key figure in Manchester's vibrant music scene. Hailing from the city's renowned Hacienda club in the early 90s, the duo's transformative fusion of techno, house, and rock breathed new life into the dance music landscape and helped redefine what it meant to be a band from Manchester. Pioneering the big beat sound and known for their explosive live shows, The Chemical Brothers have not only influenced a generation of musicians but also contributed significantly to the global success of electronic dance music.

Pop punk, New Wave, Power pop

Albums : Singles Going Steady, Buzzcocks, Product, Love Bites, Another Music in a Different Kitchen

As one of the vanguards of the punk movement in Manchester, the Buzzcocks formed in 1976, capturing the raw energy and rebellious spirit of the city's working-class youth. Their rapid-fire punk rock anthems were brimming with razor-sharp hooks and biting social commentary, making them an unforgettable force on the burgeoning punk scene. The band's DIY ethic and independent spirit were intrinsically tied to their Manchester roots, paving the way for a new wave of bands that would help shape the city's musical identity for years to come. Today, the legacy of the Buzzcocks endures as an enduring symbol of Manchester's indomitable spirit and penchant for pushing boundaries in the world of music.

Rock music, Britpop, Alternative rock

Albums : The Dreams We Have as Children – Live at the Royal Albert Hall, Rhapsody Originals

As the principal songwriter and lead guitarist of Oasis, Noel Gallagher's influential musicianship and unwavering dedication to his craft have solidified his status as a Manchester icon. Born and raised in the city's working-class neighborhood of Burnage, Gallagher's experiences and upbringing shaped the band's gritty, anthemic sound, which resonated with fans across the globe. Following the dissolution of Oasis in 2009, Noel formed his High Flying Birds project, further showcasing his ability to create new and powerful music that still echoes the spirit and determination of his beloved hometown. Through his extensive catalog and continued success, Noel Gallagher remains a vital force within Manchester's music scene, inspiring countless aspiring artists to follow in his footsteps.

Jangle pop, Indie pop, Blues-rock

Albums : The Stone Roses, Second Coming, Fools Gold, I Wanna Be Adored, Garage Flower

The Stone Roses emerged from Manchester's burgeoning alternative music scene in the late 80s, blending elements of indie rock, neo-psychedelia, and dance music to form their own unique sound. The band's innovative approach to music helped define the "Madchester" movement, capturing the imagination of fans and critics alike and setting the stage for the eventual Britpop explosion. Their eponymous debut album, often considered one of the greatest albums of all time, showcased the band's ability to seamlessly merge poetic lyricism with infectious melodies, leading to their enduring reverence within Manchester's music community. The lasting impact of The Stone Roses' discography and their role in shaping the city's musical landscape is a testament to their importance as a quintessential Manchester band.
